                            <div class="container">
                    <div class="exc-container">
                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><b>Posterior Deltoid</b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The</span> <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537056/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">deltoid</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is a large triangular muscle that sits over the shoulder and is made up of three parts. It is key in shoulder movements and provides stability to the shoulder as a postural muscle. It’s often relied upon when the rotator cuff muscles are weak.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The posterior portion of the deltoid muscle is the focus of this exercise. It is located at the back of the shoulder and plays a crucial role in shoulder movements to the back and side, as well as in outward rotation.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The posterior muscle fibers</span> <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23302754/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">activate up to 90%</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> of the maximal muscle contraction during the rear delt fly. This is why this exercise is so effective for the posterior delts. It’s important to note that the high muscle activity is associated with the</span> <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8975561/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">palms down grip position</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. If your preference is the neutral (thumbs up) hand position, fear not; it has similar activation rates.</span></p><h3><b>Upper Trapezius</b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The</span> <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK518994/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">trapezius</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> covers the shoulders, upper back, and neck. Made up of three parts, it is a large muscle resembling a trapezoid. The upper trapezius is a vital postural muscle responsible for movements like shrugging and lifting the arms overhead. It also assists in extending the neck and supporting shoulder stability.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The upper trapezius plays a key role during the rear delt fly exercise. It stabilizes the shoulder blades, allowing the rear delts to engage effectively. The stabilization helps maintain the proper form and prevents excessive strain on the shoulder joints.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The resisted rear delt fly</span> <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34911072/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">activates the upper trapezius</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> at an average rate of 55% of maximal muscle contraction. Please note that the arm position being too high or low during the exercise reduced the activation rate by up to 40%. This demonstrates how important the correct setup and form are for getting the most from your rear delt fly machine workout.</span></p>                        </div>
                    </div>
